Exercise I

a)

# Get Data ----------
us <- data.frame(read_csv(
  "~/Documents/UC Davis/Courses/STA 141A/Proj/us.csv",
  col_types = cols(
    date = col_date(format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
    cases = col_integer(),
    deaths = col_integer()
    )
  ))
# Daily and average values ----------
us["new_cases"] <- stats::filter(
  us$cases,
  c(1, -1),
  method = "convolution",
  sides = 1
  )
us["new_deaths"] <- stats::filter(
  us$deaths, c(1, -1),
  method = "convolution",
  sides = 1
  )
us["avg_new_cases"] <- stats::filter(
  us$new_cases, 
  rep(1/7, 7),
  method = "convolution",
  sides = 1
  )
us["avg_new_deaths"] <- stats::filter(
  us$new_deaths,
  rep(1/7, 7),
  method = "convolution",
  sides = 1
  )

b)

# Daily cases plot ----------
plot(
  new_cases ~ date,
  data = us,
  type = "h",
  col = "gray",
  subset = date >= "2020-03-01", 
  lwd = 2,
  ylab = "Daily Cases",
  xlab = "Date",
  main = "Daily Covid Cases in the US"
  )
lines(avg_new_cases ~ date, data = us, subset = date >= "2020-03-01", lwd = 2)

We can observe two more pronounced spikes: in the transition from 2020 to 2021 and 2021 to 2022. The most significant spike occurred at the beginning of 2022.

# Daily death plot ----------
plot(
  new_deaths ~ date, 
  data = us, 
  type = "h", 
  col = "gray",
  subset = date >= "2020-03-01", 
  lwd = 3,
  ylab = "Daily Deaths",
  xlab = "Date",
  main = "Daily Covid Deaths in the US"
  )
lines(avg_new_deaths ~ date, data = us, subset = date >= "2020-03-01", lwd = 2)

The daily deaths are relatively constant. However, we observe three peaks. First, at the start of the pandemic, we saw a significant increase, which is not an anomaly since the people most receptive to severe sickness got struck before proper measures were taken. The second and third peaks coincided with the first and second daily case peaks. Given an increase in cases, it is expected to see an increase in deaths.

There are two significant anomalies to consider. First, we have a considerable negative value in early 2022 and an enormous positive value in late 2022. Since it is not possible to have negative deaths, nor any indication of increased cases around the largely positive, we can only assume that they occurred due to sampling errors or corrections.

Question

What do you notice when comparing the plot of daily new cases in Yolo county to the analogous plot for the state of California as a whole? What might explain what you are seeing?

We observe that Yolo county follows a similar development as the state of California does in general. In the graph, California and Yolo have a somewhat flat curve up until the end of 2020, peaking in early 2021, then declining back to a flatter curve in the spring of 2021. A probable cause of such development is that in the earlier days of the pandemic, more people were prone to following guidelines, i.e., staying home, practicing social distancing, and using face masks. Hence, causation to a peak lower than the forthcoming ones. We also know that the virus has seasonal leverage—like the common flu—where it is more prone to infect and spread during the winter half of the year. Thus we should expect a higher peak in the colder months, as observed. Finally, vaccinations started around April in the US, which could also significantly influence the prolonged flattening of the curve until early 2022.

The following trends have some discrepancies between the two. We can see that California experienced a strong peak in the upcoming winter period of late 2021 to early 2022, whereas Yolo experienced a less pronounced peak. There could be several causes for that. A general thought concerning California as a state is that many people during the period when cases dropped off started to care less about restrictions; vaccinations were rolling out, and everything appeared back to normal. Nevertheless, a combination of low fully vaccinated (68%) and an even lower booster level (34%), together with the return of the seasonal potency, an unprepared California got struck with its highest daily rates. However, for Yolo, the story is slightly different.

Given that Yolo County has roughly 220,000 inhabitants, where around 40,000 of them are university students, the migration of students significantly influences the county’s statistics. There are two plausible interrelated factors to the lowered spike. First, Yolo county is a rather rurally rich area. Many people live within systematic social distancing. They are not moving around in major cities and getting exposed to hundred if not thousands of people per day. Secondly, most students do not have their origins in Yolo. Thus, many students left Davis and other college settlements in the early pandemic and returned when the campus reopened. Thus, we have a plausible explanation for why Yolo’s is less pronounced than California’s, probably because many students had yet to return to Davis.

Excercise III: Bonus

# Get and tidy data ----------
population <- read_excel(
  "~/Documents/UC Davis/Courses/STA 141A/Proj/NST-EST2022-POP.xlsx", 
  skip = 3
  )
population$state <-  sub('.', '', population$state)

# Yearly state deaths ----------
us_states["year"] <- format(as.Date(us_states$date, format="%Y-%m-%d"),"%Y")

cumulative_deaths <- us_states %>% 
  group_by(year, state) %>%
  summarise(deaths = max(deaths))

deaths_2020 <- cumulative_deaths %>% 
  filter(year == 2020) %>%
  left_join((population %>% select(state, `2020`))) %>% 
  rename(population = `2020`) %>% 
  mutate(death_capita = deaths/population*100000)

deaths_2021 <- cumulative_deaths %>% 
  filter(year == 2021) %>%
  left_join((deaths_2020 %>% select(state, deaths)), by = "state") %>% 
  transmute(year = year.x, state = state, deaths = deaths.x - deaths.y) %>% 
  left_join((population %>% select(state, `2021`))) %>% 
  rename(population = `2021`) %>% 
  mutate(death_capita = deaths/population*100000)

deaths_2022 <- cumulative_deaths %>% 
  filter(year == 2022) %>%
  left_join((deaths_2021 %>% dplyr::select(state, deaths)), by = "state") %>% 
  transmute(year = year, state = state, deaths = deaths.x - deaths.y) %>% 
  left_join((population %>% select(state, `2022`))) %>% 
  rename(population = `2022`) %>% 
  mutate(death_capita = deaths/population*100000)

deaths <- rbind(deaths_2020, deaths_2021, deaths_2022)

# State Map ----------
states <- map_data("state")
deaths$region <- tolower(deaths$state)
deaths_map <- left_join(states, deaths, by = "region")

p0 <- ggplot(
  data = deaths_map,
  mapping = aes(
    x = long, 
    y = lat,
    group = group,
    fill = death_capita
    )
  )

p1 <- p0 + 
  geom_polygon(color = "gray90", size = 0.05) +
  coord_map(projection = "albers", lat0 = 39, lat1 = 45) 

p2 <- p1 + scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma")

p2 + 
  theme_map() + 
  facet_wrap(~ year, ncol = 3) +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    strip.background = element_blank()
    ) +
  labs(
    fill = "Rate per 100,000 pop.",
    title = "Covid Related Deaths by State, 2020-2022"
    )

The plot above shows the development of Covid-related deaths from 2020-2022. We can conclude that in each state, an increase in deaths occurred. However, specific states performed better than others. For instance, Utah maintained a reasonably low death rate compared to the rest of the country, whereas New York and New Jersey saw significant increases. A probable cause could be that Utah is a rural state while the other two have a dense population.

# Add county population ----------
county_population <- read_csv(
  "~/Documents/UC Davis/Courses/STA 141A/Proj/co-est2021-alldata.csv"
  )

pops <- county_population %>% 
  select(STATE, COUNTY, STNAME, CTYNAME, POPESTIMATE2021) %>% 
  mutate(fips = paste(STATE, COUNTY, sep="")) %>% 
  select(fips, POPESTIMATE2021)

county_data <- us_counties %>% 
  group_by(fips, county) %>% 
  summarise(cumulated_deaths = max(deaths)) %>% 
  left_join(pops, by = "fips") %>% 
  mutate(death_capita = cumulated_deaths/POPESTIMATE2021*100000) %>% 
  mutate(subregion = tolower(county))

# Create Factor ----------
county_data$interval <- as.factor(cut(
  county_data$death_capita, 
  quantile(county_data$death_capita, na.rm = T)))

fltr <- levels(county_data$interval)=="(480,1.75e+03]"
levels(county_data$interval)[fltr] <- "(480,1750]"

# Map  
county_map <- map_data("county")
county_full <- left_join(county_map, county_data,  by = "subregion")

death_p <- ggplot(
  data = county_full,
  mapping = aes(
    x = long, 
    y = lat,
    fill = interval, 
    group = group
    )
  )

death_p1 <- death_p + 
  geom_polygon(color = "gray90", size = 0.05) + 
  coord_equal()

death_p2 <- death_p1 + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(n = 4, name = "Oranges"))

death_p2 + 
  labs(
    title = "Covid-Related Deaths, Cumulated 2020-2021",
    fill = "Rate per 100,000 pop.") +
  theme_map() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

This map tells a similar story as above. Although it is difficult to derive any apparent pattern, the west coast, the patch stretching from California to Utah, and the northeast coast appear to have a lower rate than the rest of the country. The same story is plausible above. The issue with this map is that we need to conclude the relative contribution of a county to the state. Take some of the northernmost states, for instance. In the map above, we can observe that they have relatively low rates, yet, in this map, we observe a lot of darker patches. Hence, without the knowledge of the map above, one could believe those states have higher death rates when, in fact, their death rates are relatively low compared to the rest of the country.
